Story:N/A
Message:We can live in a world where everyone has a roof over their head, enough food to eat and access to clean drinking water. While we have made progress, we are still a long way away from making this a reality.

Three hundred students from across the country will come together at the Resolve 2013 Conference at the University of North Carolina-Chapel Hill this October 4th-6th. We'll learn the skills and information to launch effective anti-poverty campaigns across the country, build alliances with students and advocates and be a critical part of the Resolve to Fight Poverty - a national student movement working to turn vision to reality and make sure we live in a world without poverty.

Featured events include the Oxfam Hunger Banquet, keynote address by the CEO of Feeding America, a resource fair, screening of a documentary with Q&A with the filmmakers, workshops by Campus Y organizations, and much much more!

Attend and/or help organize an annual conference being hosted by UNC Chapel Students on campus! This is an amazing opportunity to meet 200+ students from around the country and in our campus community who are Resolving to fight hunger and poverty!!!!!! 

REGISTER TODAY AT WWW.RESOLVECONFERENCE.ORG!

Message:We can live in a world where everyone has a roof over their head, enough food to eat and access to clean drinking water. While we have made progress, we are still a long way away from making this a reality.

Three hundred students from across the country will come together at the Resolve 2013 Conference at the University of North Carolina-Chapel Hill this October 4th-6th. We'll learn the skills and information to launch effective anti-poverty campaigns across the country, build alliances with students and advocates and be a critical part of the Resolve to Fight Poverty - a national student movement working to turn vision to reality and make sure we live in a world without poverty.

Featured events include the Oxfam Hunger Banquet, keynote address by the CEO of Feeding America, a resource fair, screening of a documentary with Q&A with the filmmakers, workshops by Campus Y organizations, and much much more!

Attend and/or help organize an annual conference being hosted by UNC Chapel Students on campus! This is an amazing opportunity to meet 200+ students from around the country and in our campus community who are Resolving to fight hunger and poverty!!!!!!

Story:Lulu Diaz shared a photo.
Message:A year from today I was getting ready to make one of the most challenging things in my life and I'm glad I did it because I gave life and I 've never felt more happy about anything. Ted made me remember that you only get to live once and what better than sharing with your loved ones.  
Today I'm happier because  I can proudly say  that I overcame that challenge in my life and we both are healthy.  I never thought that after a year I was going to be this strong, happy and above everything blessed with my family, friends and dancing. 
I  want to thank God for making this happening in the best possible way, to my family for always being there to support me and bring me up Mario A Palestina Lourdes D?az G Borja Christopher Diaz Mario Martinez Nad Mtz, Becca Ferris . And also I would like to thank to my new family  Cobo Brother's Dance Company because they gave me hope and something to look forward to recover faster and to pursue my dream of dancing. Thank you for your patience, coaching and hardwork James Cobo Erin Leger Milton Cobo Amber Cadwell Lawrence Armand Yin Song, I'll be always grateful that you took a chance on me.

"Live your life with no regrets, and no matter what you do, make sure you do it with a smile in your face :)"  #feelingblessed, #kidneydonor #behappy

Message:21 eh? So I need to come up with a really really special post to mark this landmark in your life.  21 years since you took your first breath. 21 first years since you put that smile on your mum and dad's face, everlasting, never fading. Proud parents of a wonderful daughter, now a wonderful young lady, stepping out in life, spreading love and happiness wherever she goes and on ever person who has the fortune to encounter her on her path. See, its so hard ot come up with something special to say. I could mention your logophilia, your passion for life, your constant struggle against bubbliness, your addiction to joi-de-vivre, but that would be too obvious. So I thought of something witty, that everyone can connect to, that everyone will just go "oh yes, that's her", something universal yet so pertinent, bewilderingly off topic on this whilst avoiding becoming floccinaucinihilipilificatious or abstentious.  'Cake"  there you go. ( can be preceded with birthday, Christmas, Easter, plain, chocolate, sweet)  No just joking.. Here is my birthday present to you.  A word, to add to your love of words, "euouae"  totally consonant free, technically a mnemonic, but now accepted as a word in itself, having existed since medieval times, long before the Boston tea party, and welsh mining villages. Not a long word, but the longest in the English language *Queen's English as ordained by her Majesty, your former head of State before you lot decided to stick to coffee and the Oxford/Cambridge English Dictionary, before Microsoft got its hands on it. (its certainly struggling with spell checking this!) Now the challenge is to find a sentence to use it in. I just hope someone else hasn't given you this word already,  imagine having two of them. Anyway, I ramble , like a capernoited cruciverbalist, and now must draw my hippopotomonstrosesquipedalian post to an end. So on this petrichorous English morning, full of psithurism, here is the recumbentibus punch line.
    
Happy  21st Birthday Hillary.  xxx  <- totally optional.

Message:Looking for a chill housemate for 2014-2015. The rent is 425$ a month before including utilities. 
I am an undergraduate student at UNC going into my second senior year. I previously had a roommate lined up; however, he scored an excellent job out of state and now I have an extra room to fill! I am friendly, laidback, fun to live with, and very easy to get along with; therefore, I am looking for someone with the same mindset. 
 My apartment is located in University Gardens Condominium community which is a short walk from campus( aprox 8 min). I would describe the general location as being off N. Columbia St. right past Longview St.; however, the exact address is 800 Pritchard Ave Ext Apt. A-17. This condo is a 2 bedroom 1.5 bath. Downstairs includes a large living room, decent kitchen and a half bath with washer and dryer, and both the bedrooms are located upstairs(I have not nearly completed furnishing the place because I have been very busy, and I would welcome all suggestions). Also, I specifically choose this location because it is located at the end of the building. This means no one shares a wall with the bedrooms or living room, and there are extra windows with allow for a great deal of natural lighting all throughout the day.
So, if you or anyone you know is looking for a last minute accommodation in Chapel Hill very close to UNC campus please feel free to message me.

ID:708705302_10152032127220303
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

Name:Charlotte Dancesport Challenge, 2013
Story:N/A
Message:Approximately 9 years ago, Amanda Kramer introduced me to this sitcom called How I Met Your Mother. We marathoned the first season together that night, and ever since it has been a huge part of the foundation of our friendship (along with the musical Chicago, Chips Ahoy cookies, and an inexplicable need to facebook stalk). Through the years that we lived half a world apart (quite literally), this show always brought us back together. It was always something we could talk about, something we could use as a jumping off point to keep in touch. Since we came to college 4 years ago, HIMYM has been our number one reason to hang out. No matter what we've got going on, no matter how busy we are, we always came together on Monday nights to watch this show and catch up on the goings on of the previous week. Despite our emotional confusion with this finale, I cannot help but express my gratitude towards this phenomenal program for all that it has done for us. We love this show, and I know that we will always be able to come home to it when we need to.

ID:1081129551_10202724390405821
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

Message:Tomorrow (Tuesday) at 3 pm the Wake County Board of Elections will be deciding whether NC State University will have a polling location on campus for the fall midterm elections. In 2012, close to 15,000 people used the polling on State's campus. Now they want to take it away. Students and faculty are coming together tomorrow for the meeting to advocate for their right to keep a polling place on campus. Please join us - we will be meeting at 1:30 pm for a planning meeting at the Common Cause offices off Glenwood and then will attend the Board's meeting. If you are interested in joining, please comment and I can give you more information.

Story:N/A
Message:Hey all,

On behalf of the Adidas NC Open committee and NCSU Badminton club, we would like to thank all of you, players, spectators, sponsors, and especially the NCSU students, for your genuine and enthusiastic support.

We hope you all had a great time at the tournament!

Congratulations to 2 of our fellow NCSU players ( Noel Mathew and Sajeesh Kumar ) who came in 1st and 2nd in the Men's Singles division C event. 

We hope all the players who took park in the tournament had a great experience participating and meeting a lot of good players.

Thanks to all the NCSU volunteers who worked as line judges, ran the registration desk, court martials, organizing and raising the enthusiasm of the tournament. 

Special thanks to Yiwen Luo, Mayu Namba, Eileen Gu, Ji Zhao, Tianheng, Ying Liao  and others who put in a lot of hard work to make this event a success.

Hope you all enjoyed taking part in playing, watching, organizing and running the tournament!

Thanks a lot,
NC Open Committee

Name:There's More to Life Than Being Happy
Story:N/A
Message:"The more one forgets himself -- by giving himself to a cause to serve or another person to love -- the more human he is." - Frankl
This article is a must read for those who question the purpose of life. I know I have always said my ultimate goal is to be happy, but happiness is a fleeting emotion. Having meaning in life gives us a sense of direction and enhances the feeling of happiness. The most powerful 'meaning' you can bestow on yourself is the desire to love and serve people.

ID:1525564424_10202481333384362
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:It has been an especially difficult few weeks for humanity.  

In times like these I hope we have each felt uncomfortable with ourselves and the justifications we are each capable of making for violence and murder. The conflicts are over borders these days--real estate--and between the developing stories about Mexican, Palestinian, Israeli, Dutch, Malaysian men, women, children, it became hard to pick sides, and that's exactly what we've been asked to do by politics and the arrival of these stories on the social media scene. "I don't know man, I'm not really sure which side I'm on" I was told at dinner in response to my question about the recent invasion of Gaza. Today, that's not the right question. When the rockets stop falling, it might be. But it's about time we dropped the justifications for civilian casualties on all sides and caught up with history.

Has morality lost its urgency?

ID:1531609000_10201669923259817
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

ID:1576786774_10201984632728863
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Looking up things to do in Dhaka anddd came upon this! It's like they know our lives!

"5. Dinner and karaoke at Pyongyang: Although Bangladesh doesn?t have a large community of expats, South Korea?s business interests in the country ? it?s the largest investor in special export zones ? mean a growing number of South Koreans live there. Ask a Dhaka resident for a food recommendation and they?re just as likely to recommend a Korean restaurant as one serving Bangla food ? in fact, more likely. Pyongyang is not among the best of them, in terms of food. In fact, it?s not even South Korean. But it?s still worth a visit.

Opened three years ago, it is part of a state-run chain of North Korean restaurants that have opened in parts of Asia with South Korean populations. Located in a home in the enclave of Banani, waitresses in baby pink hanbok ? long-sleeved shiny gowns that slightly evoke Victorian nighties ? serve diners. They also play the violin and croon Korean numbers, urging customers to sing along or select their own songs. Customers who don?t sing, even after the microphone has been thrust into their hands, get angry glances. Don?t eat the batter-fried fish, but do try the kimchi rice."

ID:1734510749_4339962593968
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:ESPN rates Coach K No. 4 best men's college basketball coach in recent years. Here are some interesting stats: Since 2006-07, Duke has won just 1 regular season ACC title. In 6 of those 8 seasons, Duke failed to progress past the Sweet 16. In 3 of those 6 seasons, they lost their 1st NCAA tournament game. In 2 of the last 3 years, they've been sent home right away, by a No. 15 and No. 14 seed, respectively. But, from Nov. 26, 2007, to Jan. 6, 2014, Duke never once ranked outside the Associated Press top 10. The Blue Devils spent 122 straight weeks without falling below No.10, the longest streak since Wooden's UCLA Bruins from 1966-1976. They won it all in 2010. Those stats epitomize Duke in my recent memory.

Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Candlelight Vigil for Dr. Feng Liu at Global FedEx Center. 

As you may know, Dr. Liu was beaten and robbed on University Drive at 1pm after lunch one day, a road very close to campus that many students, professors, and staff leisurely walk on during various parts of the day. Dr. Liu died from his wounds.

Many friends, colleagues, neighbors, and members of the community attended candlelight vigil, even at a late notice of a few days. It was touching to see so many faces and heart-breaking to hear different speeches and tributes to Dr. Liu.

Everyone, please be safe where ever you are, no matter how often you have been there before. It really is important that you don't walk around at night alone. Even during broad daylight in a comfortable area, you do need to be aware of your surroundings. My thoughts go out to Dr. Liu's family and friends. ?????????.

Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

Message:To all my veterans, student veterans, and active duty military, I have the opportunity to voice our opinions, challenges, and successes in higher education at The American Legions National Convention. I would love to hear from all of you as well. 

What have some of your struggles been while attending a 4 year university, community college, private institution, or any technical school? G.I. Bill, faculty/staff, community, or student affairs issues that you have came a crossed and how you did or did not over come them? 

This is a great chance for you to express your opinions and a chance for them to be heard by policy makers and veteran organizations that enforce them. Thank you all and most of all thank you for your service!

ID:100001043113693_771080102936753
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

In collaboration with students from NC State!! 

Hear our alumni speak about their experiences as you experience the campus for yourself. Learn about our beautiful Carolina campus, campus life, and learn about the college application process, including financial aid, and find what you should be looking out for as you make your decisions about what to do about post-secondary education. 

For the first time in HSAC history, we are holding a session for community college students!! Community college Students can learn about the college transferring process from our experienced students who have made the transfer to UNC-Chapel Hill. Come ask us questions and learn more about your options and what you can do to make the transfer process better for yourself!

We are excited!! And we want you to be excited about our tour and about your education! Let us help prepare you to take control of your future! Join us on April 5th! Wear comfortable shoes! ;) Bring money for dinner on Franklin Street, the center of night life and thrill in downtown Chapel Hill, conveniently located right next to campus.

Email your registration form to Miss Leigh Taylor or Miss Cherish Khang by THURSDAY APRIL 3rd, and have your fees ready when you board the bus at Bunker Hill High School. 

Visit our event page to access the Registration form and for more information. Feel free to post questions! You can also contact:
Miss Leigh Taylor (leighsht@live.unc.edu / 336.880.0595) or 
Miss Cherish Khang (nckhang@live.unc.edu / 980.213.5661) for more info, and if your have question or concerns about the tour. Hope to see you there!

ID:100001653027114_714462268618867
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:I... am... so... tired. I probably messed up somewhere and could've combined things or something to make it all easier/faster, but geez. -.- And looking back on it, I realize I missed another unit build accelerator factor. DARN IT! If only sleep deprivation was this useful ALL the time. 

I just did math. Lots of math:

Assuming Maxed Out Building: 0:13:39 = 819 Seconds / Speed 2 World = 409.5 Seconds per Unit.
Assuming Hero Bonus: 60% Recruitment reduction = -245.7 Seconds = 163.8 Seconds per Unit.
Assuming Spell Bonus: 50% Recruitment reduction = 81.9 Seconds per Unit.
Assuming Special Reward Bonus: 20% Recruitment reduction = -16.38 Seconds = 65.52 Seconds per Unit.
Assuming Quest Reward Bonus: 30% Recruitment reduction = -19.66 Seconds = 45.86 Seconds per Unit.

Thus, you can make 78.5 Units per Hour; 1k Units in 12 Hours & 2k Units in 25 Hours. 

Resources Required for 1 Unit: 75 Stone & 150 Silver.
Assuming Research Done: Costs reduced by 10% = 67.5 Stone & 135 Silver.
Assuming Hero Bonus: Costs reduced by 60% = 27 Stone & 84 Silver.

Thus, 1k Units Require 27k Stone & 84k Silver & 2k Units Require 54k Stone & 168k Silver. 

Warehouse Caps at 25.5k of each resource. 
Resource Levels: Stone = 699/Hour & Silver = 852/Hour. 
For 1k Units: 38 Hours for enough Stone & 98 Hours for enough Silver.
Assuming Spell Bonus: Resource Levels 50% Boost =1048.5 Stone &  1278 Silver/Hour; therefore, ~26 hours & ~66 hours needed.

549 Wood/Hour --> 823 Wood. 
2k Wood Trades for 2.5k Silver. 
Assume minimum of 3 Trade Ports = 6k Wood for 7.5k Silver.
Trade Ratio drops by 0.03 per 100 Traded Resources.
2000 Resources / 100 Resources = 20 X 0.03 = 0.60 Ratio Drop.
1.25 - 0.60 = 0.65 Trade Ratio.
Trade Ratio increases by 0.02 every hour until cap.
0.60 / 0.02 = 3 hours; 7.5k Silver every 3 hours.

852 Silver/Hour for 26 hours = 22152 Silver. 
26 Hours / 3 Hours = 8 X 7.5k Silver = 60k Silver --> 82152 Silver.

Assume looting from 8 points every 20 minutes. 
Each point = 80 Resources X 8 Points = 640 Silver / 20 Minutes. 
26 Hours = 1560 Minutes / 20 Minutes = 78 Times X 640 Silver = 49920 Silver. 

Sooo about 14k Shot in Silver. Allies send up to 10k Silver. Move Silver from other areas to current area or spell silver.

Overall, 1k Units can be created within 25 hours in the best case scenario. In ideal situations, around 30 hours. Realistically... maybe 48 hours. 

[C/P is... in lack of a better term: OP!]

Message:Sales & Marketing High School Representatives (Now Accepting Applications!)

To those who are now studying at U.S. high schools:
Are you interested in real-world business? Do you want to show your leadership skills through meaningful extracurricular experiences? Are you seeking ways to make a real impact on your community? Do you want to join a company run by top U.S. college students and earn management positions in your college years?

Then join us! We partner with Findingschool.net and have established the ?Finding Your Leaper Program?. As a Sales & Marketing Representative at the U.S. high schools, you would collaborate with top U.S. college students to carry out marketing plans, improve our services and gain first-hand exposure to the business world. 

Benefits:
1. Great resume boost for college application
2. Networking opportunities with college students from Harvard, Princeton, UPenn, Duke and many more!
3. Opportunities to show your leadership, marketing and business skills
4. A possibility to take management-level positions in college years
5. Rewards available from sales

Requirements:
1. A junior or senior in a U.S. high school
2. Outstanding performance in academic and extracurricular activities
3. Great communication skills
4. Responsible and able to meet time commitment (1-3 hours/week)
5. Ability to effectively reach out to targeted student populations

Responsibilities:
1. Design and execute a local marketing strategy with the goal of growing awareness and participation in Leap
2. Develop original content, including videos, stories, posters, and other multimedia assets to promote Leap
3. Other job duties as assigned

Deadline?January 25th?2013

How to apply?
Please write a short essay (less than 250 words) about why you want to join Leap and how you would contribute to our program. Please email your essay and your most recent academic transcript to leap.program.usa@gmail.com

After receiving your application, we will conduct phone interviews to qualified candidates. We would accept candidates on a rolling basis. Since the spots fill up quickly, please apply as soon as possible. The last day to apply is January 25th, 2013, but we are very likely to close our admission before then.

Please check more relevant information at: www.leap-usa.com
We are looking forward to speaking with you about your interests!



Leap Consulting Co.Ltd.
A Peer Mentor Program for International Students at U.S. High Schools
www.leap-usa.com
leap.program.usa@gmail.com

ID:100002209942621_622660121150980
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

ID:100002739888196_477894062311919
Name:null
Story:Crystalcrazy Zheng was tagged in Chengliang Fann's photo.
Message:N/A
ID:100002739888196_476660382435287
Name:null
Story:Crystalcrazy Zheng added 9 photos.
Message:I was asked before those 24 hours whether dancers should be there all the 24 hours. ?They should be there the whole time?? ?No one would know if they leave right?? To be honest, I had the same question back then as well. I even thought that ?stand? meant just staying there rather than literally standing. If you were tired, you could sit; if you were sleepy, you could simply sleep on the ground. 

I was asked before those 24 hours whether dancers kept dancing the whole time. ?What is the point of standing for 24 hours? I understand why dancers need to raise at least 150 dollars but I can?t figure out why they should be standing for that long? I felt the same way and had no idea how to response. 

I was asked before those 24 hours about why I was in the committee of DM. ?What can you gain out of this organization?? I was kind of tongue-tied at that moment and did not really know the answer myself.

It was finally Friday night, the night of the 16th annual DM. 

In the first six or seven hours, everyone was in high spirits and was full of energy; the place was like a giant dancing floor of a bar that could hold and was holding thousands of people. Different from a bar, people inside were not excited and elated by alcohol; rather, with a sober mind and for a pure and wonderful dream, they gathered together in the same place and danced better than any dancers in any single bar. 

When it was 3ish am, I wondered why there were much fewer people in the gym, only to find that a lot of them went to the study room to lean on the table, or stood on their heads on the wall, or put their feet on the handrails of the stairs, or helped others to lift up their legs. Anyway there were all sorts of funny and cute poses that could help ease the pain. Yet no matter how exhausted and painful, there was not even a single person on the spot breaking the promise made before; there was not even a single person trying to sit down for just a little while. I heard people say something like ?I want my bed?, ?I?ve never wanted to sit on the ground so bad?, ?I can?t feel my feet? and ?We got this we can do it? but I didn?t hear anything like ?Let?s just sit down?. 

Kenan walk was no doubt one of the most amazing experiences there. Even though we did not get to see the sunrise, even though there was not an exciting game going on, we still got to see the kind of spaciousness that you thought you were overlooking yet you were actually being held by, the kind of transition up in the sky from dark to indigo to Carolina blue, the kind of hope that a brand new day granted. 

The following eleven hours went by much more slowly than those hours passed. Still, in no way could I see anyone give up or sit down. ?A new day! Tell yourself you have slept for 8 hours last night?. 

The final two hours answered all the doubts I had in the very beginning, and was definitely the climax of the 24 hours. 

The kid co-captains and their families represented by each dancing team came to the stage. Then there was a fantastic talent show by several kids. The dance performed by the family in pink dresses impressed me a lot. With the most radiant and sincere smile on the face, the little girl on the wheelchair wiggled her arms, forming a heart-warming dance. Waves of cheering broke over the dance--the excitement of atmosphere was no less than that of the scene where everyone sang ?hark the sound? together upon winning the basketball game 20 hours ago. (And yeah, we watched the basketball game together at 8ish on Friday night!) What hundreds of people offered to the kids with physical or mental defect were more support, help, encouragement and love than discrimination or indifference. In such powerful and affecting positive energy, I tried my best to fight back my tears yet still burst into tears. A variety of feelings trigger those tears: tiredness, the power created by all the tough and nice people around you, the warmth brought by the smiles and strength of the kids, the sudden realization of why everyone would stand for 24 hours. Can?t tell for sure which feeling was the most predominant; all of the different feelings mixed and brewed, together moved one to tears. Next, a mom of twins and a dad of a girl shared their stories of their children. The simple and unadorned words and the peaceful tone conveyed the heart wracking yet remarkable stories, making us truly understand the meaning of the 24 hours and the meaning of Dance Marathon. 

The father said, ?It?s like a fortune 5 hundred company, but it?s being run by people that, on top of all of the rigorous studies, on top of, you know basketball games and club sports and Greek life and all the things that take your time to have spent in doing something, you know, it is not just the 24 hours of dance, this goes on the entire year, you will start to have committee meeting in two weeks to start talking about next year. It?s just an unbelievable thing you guys do. I tell Ashlyn all the time 'Become the change you wanna see in the world', and you guys are doing it, thank you guys." I was at the very front of the stage so I could see that the father lowered his head and tried to fight back his tears at times. I guess, there was definitely a touching feeling evoked by hundreds of dancers under the stage and an organization that was making the world better and better bit by bit. 

The chancellor said, ?This is Carolina. This is what I know and love about Carolina. You do great things with style, with energy and are having so much fun.? 

By the end, everyone formed a huge circle, hugging each other shoulder to shoulder even though they didn?t know each other. 

After the 24 hours, the whole gym was filled with balloons of a riot of color; everyone SIT DOWN. 

All doubts have been solved. If before this I were told by someone that you could stand for 24 hours with the help of willpower, I would not believe it. Now I get to understand and believe as well. One does not necessarily need to have a so-called strong body to afford staying up for 24 hours since it is an atmosphere permeated with conviction and love as well as a beautiful goal the 24 hours can help reach that grant one the super power to make it.

What standing for 5 hours and standing for 24 hours can offer to others might be the same but how one feels about standing for 5 hours and 24 hours should absolutely be different. At least my feelings changed every several hours, which was sort of beyond words but was amazing. And I guess feelings are some powerful chemicals that motivate actions so maybe this somehow forms a virtuous cycle. 

But I still don?t have a definite answer as for what I can get from DM, not because it gives me nothing, but because it gives me something too big to express in an accurate way with my clumsy words. It?s genuinely something that one has to experience and feel to gradually understand. 

And some words read from an article occurred to me, ?it isn?t necessary to request answers from life in a hurry; sometimes, you really need to wait with patience. Even if you shouted in a valley, you would need to wait for a while until the long echo finds its way back.?

Before stop writing, I need to thank Renee for giving me the chance to join Pub and leading me to integrate with it, and thank Erin for teaching me all the stuff about video editing and for all the helping and caring, and thank all the girls in Pub for making it a great committee! #Publove

PS: I know this is long-winded, and words just can't do justice to how awesome it was. But trust me, it is too awesome to not to do it.  DO IT TOGETHER NEXT YEAR!!

ID:100006641705075_712707735416524
Name:null
Story:Katrina Wertz posted an event to Facss China's timeline.
Message:This month of February, Carolina China Network is excited to present a discussion entitled China & Africa: Define the Relationship on Friday, February 28th from 4-5pm in Union Room 3206.  We are keen on exposing students on our campus to the myriad of reasons why China has turned attention to Africa?s continent and what opportunities and consequences have come about.  The short one-hour event will be a great chance to come together and eat free Chinese dumplings and discuss economic, diplomatic, and cultural collaborations from a high-level viewpoint.  Our goal is for each person in the room to hear, share, and learn something new about the Sino-Africa relationship that they may not have heard or considered before, and to meet someone in the room that you could continue the conversation with beyond this event!

    ???????????????? ???????????????? ??????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????????

 

 

    Jim Morgan  was named  President  and CEO  of Krispy  Kreme Doughnuts, Inc. in January 2008. Mr. Morgan has been a member of the Krispy  Kreme  Board  of Directors  since  2000  and was elected its Chairman in 2005.

 

    Mr. Morgan served as Chairman and CEO of Wachovia Securities following the acquisition of Interstate/Johnson Lane, Inc. (IJL) by Wachovia  Corporation.   He  also  served  as Chairman  and  CEO of Interstate/Johnson Lane, Inc.. Mr. Morgan is a past member of the Securities Industry Association Board of Directors and the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) regional firms committee, and is currently on the Board of Directors of Coca-Coca Bottling Company Consolidated. Mr. Morgan has more than 40 years of business experience and is a

1969 graduate of Vanderbilt University. He also served as a lieutenant in the U.S. Navy.
